odule-selection#choosing-between-similar-modules","content":"Use `yieldless/iterable` when the input is a stream or async generator."},"227":{"id":"/docs/guides/module-selection-98","page_id":"/docs/guides/module-selection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/module-selection#choosing-between-similar-modules","content":"Use `yieldless/singleflight` when duplicate callers ask for the same work at the same time. It is not a cache."},"228":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"page","content":"Quickstart","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Guides","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart"},"229":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"Get a Yieldless application flow working with tuple errors, cancellation, and one realistic boundary."},"230":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#install","content":"Install"},"231":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"Step 1: stop throwing for routine failures"},"232":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"Step 2: group related work under one cancellation signal"},"233":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Step 3: add retries where the outside world is unreliable"},"234":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"Step 4: keep the edges boring"},"235":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#a-full-request-flow","content":"A full request flow"},"236":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-7","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Where to go next"},"237":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-8","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#common-mistakes","content":"Common mistakes"},"238":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-9","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#good-keep-tuple-boundaries-explicit","content":"Good: keep tuple boundaries explicit"},"239":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-10","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-carrying-tuples-through-every-layer","content":"Avoid: carrying tuples through every layer"},"240":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#good-pass-cancellation-into-real-io","content":"Good: pass cancellation into real I/O"},"241":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-expecting-yieldless-to-stop-work-that-ignores-signals","content":"Avoid: expecting Yieldless to stop work that ignores signals"},"242":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"The fastest way to understand Yieldless is to wire the core pieces together:"},"243":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/error` to keep failures in tuple form"},"244":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/result` when tuple branches need light composition"},"245":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/task`, `yieldless/all`, `yieldless/iterable`, `yieldless/queue`, `yieldless/pubsub`, and `yieldless/limiter` to fan work out, hand it off, and control pressure"},"246":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/retry`, `yieldless/schedule`, `yieldless/signal`, `yieldless/timer`, and `yieldless/breaker` for resilient async boundaries"},"247":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/cache`, `yieldless/batcher`, and `yieldless/singleflight` for repeated, keyed, and duplicate work"},"248":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"Boundary adapters like `yieldless/fetch`, `yieldless/schema`, `yieldless/router`, `yieldless/ipc`, `yieldless/node`, and `yieldless/env`"},"249":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#install","content":"TypeScript 5.5+ is the target baseline. The package is compiled with `isolatedDeclarations` enabled."},"250":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"`safeTry()` and `safeTrySync()` let you treat common failures as data instead of exception control flow."},"251":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"That pattern is the center of the library. Every module is designed to fit back into the same `[error, value]` shape."},"252":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"When a tuple flow grows past one branch, use `yieldless/result` to keep it readable."},"253":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"Keep this modest. If one `if (error)` branch is clearer, use the branch."},"254":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"`runTaskGroup()` gives you a shared abort signal and sibling failure propagation."},"255":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"If `readRefs()` throws, the group aborts the shared signal, waits for `readStatus()` to settle, and then rethrows the original failure.\nIf the request or UI flow already has an `AbortSignal`, pass it in so the whole group inherits upstream cancellation."},"256":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"When the work is a list rather than a few named tasks, use `mapLimit()` to keep pressure on the outside world under control."},"257":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"The result order matches the input order, and the first tuple error aborts the remaining in-flight work."},"258":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"For async streams or generators, reach for `yieldless/iterable` instead of materializing everything first."},"259":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Retries should stay close to transport boundaries: HTTP, queues, database connections, and subprocesses that can legitimately fail for transient reasons."},"260":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"The retry loop respects `AbortSignal`, so if a parent task group is canceled, the pending backoff timer is canceled too."},"261":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"When a boundary needs a firm time budget, derive one signal and pass it through the whole call chain."},"262":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"If you are calling HTTP JSON APIs, `yieldless/fetch` combines the same ideas:"},"263":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"If you need to wait for eventual consistency, use `poll()` instead of hand-writing timers."},"264":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"The package ships helpers for common backend boundaries and production pressure:"},"265":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/env` validates startup configuration"},"266":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/fetch` wraps HTTP status, JSON parsing, and deadlines"},"267":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/schema` keeps validators in tuple form"},"268":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/router` turns tuple handlers into HTTP responses"},"269":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/ipc` preserves tuple results across Electron IPC"},"270":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/node` wraps filesystem and child-process work"},"271":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/event` waits for one event with cleanup and abort support"},"272":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/schedule` builds reusable retry and repeat policies"},"273":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/limiter` protects shared capacity with semaphores and rate limits"},"274":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/queue` and `yieldless/pubsub` coordinate in-process workers and subscribers"},"275":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-46","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/cache` keeps successful read-through loads fresh for a TTL"},"276":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-47","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/batcher` collapses nearby keyed reads into ordered batches"},"277":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-48","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/breaker` backs off dependencies that are already failing"},"278":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-49","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/singleflight` deduplicates duplicate in-flight work"},"279":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-50","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/test` makes promises, clocks, and abort signals deterministic in tests"},"280":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-51","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Module Selection when you are deciding which helper fits a specific problem."},"281":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-52","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Design Rules before you spread the tuple style across a large codebase."},"282":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-53","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Do and Don't if you are moving a team onto the library and want the conventions to stay sharp."},"283":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-54","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Use the reference section when you already know what module you need."},"284":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-55","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-carrying-tuples-through-every-layer","content":"Most UI and domain code wants ordinary values or ordinary state. Convert at the boundary."},"285":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"page","content":"Bounded Batch Work","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work"},"286":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Process lists of API, filesystem, or subprocess work without unbounded parallelism."},"287":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#refresh-several-repositories","content":"Refresh several repositories"},"288":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Why this is friendlier"},"289":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"Good variation: stream the input"},"290":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"Avoid: unbounded fan-out"},"291":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"This recipe is for the common \"do this for every item\" path: refresh every repo, fetch every avatar, resize every image, or inspect every file. The work is independent, but starting it all at once can make a user's machine or an upstream service miserable."},"292":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when you want tuple errors, shared cancellation, stable output order, and a hard ceiling on active work."},"293":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Output order matches `repositories`, so UI code does not need to sort the result back into place."},"294":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"The first tuple error aborts in-flight work and stops starting new items."},"295":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"A parent `AbortSignal` can cancel the whole batch when the user navigates away."},"296":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"`concurrency` is explicit, so expensive work stays polite by default."},"297":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"If repositories come from an async source, use `yieldless/iterable` instead of building a large array first."},"298":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"That can launch dozens or hundreds of subprocesses. Use `mapLimit()` or `mapAsyncLimit()` so the user’s machine stays responsive."},"299":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"page","content":"Electron Git Client","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client"},"300":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"An end-to-end shape for a desktop Git app using IPC tuples, abortable subprocesses, and typed renderer calls."},"301":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"302":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"303":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"304":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#renderer-usage","content":"Renderer usage"},"305":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Why this boundary feels cleaner"},"306":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"307":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"308":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"Yieldless fits Electron well because the important boundaries in an Electron app are all failure-heavy: the renderer asks for work through IPC, the main process touches the filesystem, the main process launches long-running child processes like `git clone`."},"309":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"If the window is torn down or a parent task group is canceled, the subprocess is aborted through Node's native child-process signal handling."},"310":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The renderer never depends on Electron's lossy thrown-error conversion."},"311":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The main process can use the same tuple style it uses everywhere else."},"312":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Long-running Git subprocesses can be canceled as soon as the UI no longer cares about them."},"313":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate status reads if several panels can request the same repository at once."},"314":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Wait for one app or window event with cleanup."},"315":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Do not expose arbitrary IPC channels to the renderer."},"316":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Build a small preload bridge with `createIpcBridge()` or `createAbortableIpcBridge()` so the renderer only sees the operations it is allowed to call."},"317":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"page","content":"Electron PR Review Workbench","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench"},"318":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"A practical architecture for a GitHub pull-request review desktop app using tuples in the right places and ordinary UI state in the renderer."},"319":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"320":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"321":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"322":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"Renderer state"},"323":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Why this fits PR review tools well"},"324":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"325":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"326":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Rule of thumb"},"327":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"If you are building a GitHub PR review app in Electron, Yieldless fits best in the main process, preload bridge, and service layer. It is less useful as the shape of your React component state."},"328":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"That distinction matters:"},"329":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Use tuples while you are still doing failure-heavy work: GitHub API calls, local Git reads, diff parsing, cache reads, IPC boundaries."},"330":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Once the renderer receives the result, fold it into ordinary screen state and move on."},"331":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"The important thing here is not the exact helper list. It is the layering:"},"332":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/error` keeps the boundary readable with `ok()` and `err()`."},"333":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/all` loads the PR payload in parallel."},"334":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/task` gives the whole request one shared cancellation signal."},"335":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/node` keeps Git subprocess failures in the same tuple contract."},"336":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"This is the point where Yieldless should usually stop being the dominant shape."},"337":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"That keeps the renderer normal. Components render `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, or `error`. They do not need to carry `[error, value]` through every prop."},"338":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Pull-request work crosses many noisy boundaries: GitHub HTTP, local Git, caches, and Electron IPC."},"339":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Cancellation matters because users jump between PRs quickly and the old load should stop being important."},"340":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"The renderer wants stable view state, not a low-level transport shape."},"341":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate duplicate PR loads while a user is switching tabs or refreshing panels."},"342":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Use bounded iterable work when processing many files in a diff."},"343":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-25","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Do not keep tuples as your component model."},"344":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-26","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Fold the tuple once into `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, and `error` state. UI code should speak in screen states."},"345":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-27","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Use Yieldless in the main process and preload boundary."},"346":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-28","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Convert tuples into domain state at the renderer edge."},"347":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-29","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Do not force tuple results deep into component trees."},"348":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"page","content":"Resilient Service Flow","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow"},"349":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"A practical backend flow that combines tuples, retries, validation, routing, and cancellation."},"350":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"The moving parts"},"351":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#route-handler","content":"Route handler"},"352":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Why this holds up well in production"},"353":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#good-variation-add-a-remote-dependency","content":"Good variation: add a remote dependency"},"354":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#avoid-retrying-the-whole-handler","content":"Avoid: retrying the whole handler"},"355":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Rules worth keeping"},"356":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"This recipe shows the shape Yieldless is best at: an HTTP request that validates input, performs a few pieces of I/O, retries the flaky part, and returns a normal JSON response."},"357":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/schema` validates input without throwing"},"358":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps HTTP calls in tuple form"},"359":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/retry` handles transient I/O noise"},"360":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/task` keeps sibling work under one cancellation signal"},"361":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/router` turns tuple results into a plain response"},"362":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Validation failures never take the exception path."},"363":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"If `loadRefs()` fails, `loadStatus()` is aborted immediately."},"364":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Retry timers are cancellable because they run through `AbortSignal`."},"365":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"The handler body stays linear. There is no framework-specific DSL to learn."},"366":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#good-variation-add-a-remote-dependency","content":"The retry policy is attached to the flaky network call, not to the whole request."},"367":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#avoid-retrying-the-whole-handler","content":"That repeats validation, routing decisions, and any side effects. Retry the noisy boundary instead."},"368":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Validate early and return early."},"369":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Retry only the noisy boundary, not the entire request."},"370":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Spawn sibling work only when both tasks should die together."},"371":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Map domain misses to explicit HTTP errors like `NotFoundError`."},"372":{"id":"/docs/reference/all","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"page","content":"yieldless/all","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all"},"373":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all","content":"Tuple-aware parallel combinators that share cancellation."},"374":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"Exports"},"375":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#example","content":"Example"},"376":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"Behavior notes"},"377":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-4","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#when-to-prefer-runtaskgroup-instead","content":"When to prefer runTaskGroup() instead"},"378":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-5","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Good"},"379":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-6","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"380":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-7","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all","content":"`yieldless/all` gives you helpers for tuple-returning parallel work: `all(tasks)` waits for every task or aborts siblings on the first error, `race(tasks)` resolves with the first settled result and aborts the rest, and `mapLimit(items, mapper, options)` processes a collection with bounded concurrency."},"381":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-8","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`type SafeTask<T, E = Error> = (signal: AbortSignal) => PromiseLike<SafeResult<T, E>> | SafeResult<T, E>`"},"382":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-9","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`type MapLimitMapper<Item, Value, E = Error> = (item: Item, index: number, signal: AbortSignal) => PromiseLike<SafeResult<Value, E>> | SafeResult<Value, E>`"},"383":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-10","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`all(tasks, options): Promise<SafeResult<AllValues<Tasks>, ParallelError<Tasks>>>`"},"384":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-11","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`mapLimit(items, mapper, { concurrency, signal }): Promise<SafeResult<Value[], E>>`"},"385":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-12","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`race(tasks, options): Promise<SafeResult<Value, Error>>`"},"386":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-13","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#example","content":"For large batches, use `mapLimit()` to avoid starting every item at once:"},"387":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-14","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`all([])` succeeds with an empty array."},"388":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-15","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`mapLimit([], mapper, options)` succeeds with an empty array."},"389":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-16","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`mapLimit()` preserves input order and throws a `RangeError` when `concurrency` is less than `1` or not an integer."},"390":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-17","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`race([])` throws a `RangeError`."},"391":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-18","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"If any task or mapped item returns `[error, null]`, siblings are aborted before the final tuple is returned."},"392":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-19","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`race()` aborts losing tasks immediately, then waits for them to settle before it returns."},"393":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-20","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"Thrown task and mapper failures are normalized into tuple failures internally."},"394":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-21","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#when-to-prefer-runtaskgroup-instead","content":"Use `all()`, `race()`, and `mapLimit()` when the work is already tuple-native. Use `runTaskGroup()` when you want imperative fan-out and regular promise values."},"395":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-22","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `all()` for a small, fixed set of independent tuple tasks."},"396":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-23","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when a list could be large or expensive."},"397":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-24","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `race()` when the first success or first failure should settle the operation."},"398":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-25","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#avoid","content":"Do not pass work that ignores the signal and expect cancellation to be immediate."},"399":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-26","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#avoid","content":"Do not use `all()` for thousands of items. Use `mapLimit()` or `yieldless/iterable` so you can control pressure."},"400":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"page","content":"yieldless/batcher","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher"},"401":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher","content":"DataLoader-style keyed batching for tuple-returning async reads."},"402":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"Exports"},"403":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#example","content":"Example"},"404":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/do